Hi,
I've been playing with the C# wrapper. My initial goal is to get the depth image aligned to the colour image and alter pixels in the colour image based on their depth.
Starting with the cs-tutorial-2-capture example, I've added an instance of the Align class using:
 `align = new Align(Stream.Color);` 
and then in the while loop added:

```
var aligned = align.Process(frames);
var colorized_aligned_depth = colorizer.Colorize(aligned.DepthFrame);
UploadImage(imgColor, colorized_aligned_depth);
```

(replacing the UploadImage call for the raw colour image, just want to see the raw depth next to the aligned depth for now)
However, after a few frames I keep getting an System.AccessViolationException ('Attempted to read or write protected memory. This is often an indication that other memory is corrupt.') traced back to Processing.cs line 100 (NativeMethods.rs2_process_frame in Align.Process), and inspecting the FrameSet input for that method under debug I can see that the DepthFrame is null. Adding a null check before calling Process doesn't seem to help, it can often pass the null check immediately before calling then be null by the time it gets to the native call.
I figured it may be something to do with not releasing things, as the Readme for the wrapper (https://github.com/IntelRealSense/librealsense/tree/master/wrappers/csharp/readme.md) says you should call release on everything (though the sample doesn't), but after wrapping everything in using blocks so the inside of my while loop looks like this:

```
using (var frames = pipeline.WaitForFrames())
{
    if (frames.DepthFrame == null || frames.ColorFrame == null)
        continue;

    using (var colorized_depth = colorizer.Colorize(frames.DepthFrame))
    {
        UploadImage(imgDepth, colorized_depth);
    }
                                
    using (var aligned = align.Process(frames))
    using (var colorized_aligned_depth = colorizer.Colorize(aligned.DepthFrame))
    {
        UploadImage(imgColor, colorized_aligned_depth);
    }
}
```

I still get the same exception after about 10 seconds, but this time in Frame.cs line 54 (the Release method).

Can anyone help resolve this please? Am I using anything incorrectly or is this an issue with the wrapper?

BTW, I also had problems running the sample out of the box before making any changes as the colour image from the SR300 is 16 bits per pixel but the BitmapSource.Create call in UploadImage expects 24 bits so I get System.ArgumentException: 'Value does not fall within the expected range.'.

Thanks!

From http://docs.graphene-python.org/en/latest/execution/middleware/#example:

```
class AuthorizationMiddleware(object):
    def resolve(self, next, root, info, **args):
        if info.field_name == 'user':
            return None
        return next(root, info, **args)
```

Results in:

> graphql.error.located_error.GraphQLLocatedError: resolve() missing 1 required positional argument: 'info'

It was only due to stumbling across #612 that I read this:

> self not being a class instance in resolver 'methods'. I don't understand the architectural reasons why this can't be the case, but in Python an instance method (like the resolver methods) is expected to take a self first argument. The documentation says that this isn't the case with Graphene (which is unexpected), but it still calls the argument self in some cases which further confuses the issue. It is mentioned that these methods act like static methods, however it's unexpected that they aren't decorated with the `@staticmethod` decorator.

Which works:

```
class AuthorizationMiddleware(object):
    def resolve(next, root, info, **args): # remove `self` as first param
        if info.field_name == 'user':
            return None
        return next(root, info, **args)
```

After setting the width to '100%' (or any relative width) in CKEDITOR_CONFIGS, the widget does not look as expected. It does seem to work with absolute widths (e.g., '500px'), but not for relative widths. 

Temporarily solved this by defining the width of the django-ckeditor-widget class in my css stylesheet, but I assume there must be a better way. 

`.django-ckeditor-widget {
    width: 100%;
}`
